04205nam a22004695i 9780226923758DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132012ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226923758  a(DE-B1597)523664  a(OCoLC)823010496  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a155.9/22231 aPettit, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Science of Deception :bPsychology and Commerce in America /cMichael Pettit. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2013] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b5 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. “Graft Is the Worst Form of Despotism”: Swindlers, Commercial Culture, and the Deceivable Self -- tChapter Two. Hunting Duck-Rabbits: Illusions, Mass Culture, and the Law of Economy -- tChapter Three. “Not Our Houses but Our Brains Are Haunted”: The Arts of Exposure at the Boundaries of Credulity -- tChapter Four. The Unwary Purchaser: Trademark Infringement, the Deceivable Self, and the Subject of Consumption -- tChapter Five. Diagnosing Deception: Pathological Lying, Lie Detectors, and the Normality of the Deceitful Self -- tChapter Six. Studies in Deceit: Personality Testing and the Character of Experiments -- tConclusion. Barnum’s Ghost Gives an Encore Performance -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDuring the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries, Americans were fascinated with fraud. P. T. Barnum artfully exploited the American yen for deception, and even Mark Twain championed it, arguing that lying was virtuous insofar as it provided the glue for all interpersonal intercourse. But deception was not used solely to delight, and many fell prey to the schemes of con men and the wiles of spirit mediums. As a result, a number of experimental psychologists set themselves the task of identifying and eliminating the illusions engendered by modern, commercial life. By the 1920s, however, many of these same psychologists had come to depend on deliberate misdirection and deceitful stimuli to support their own experiments. The Science of Deception explores this paradox, weaving together the story of deception in American commercial culture with its growing use in the discipline of psychology. Michael Pettit reveals how deception came to be something that psychologists not only studied but also employed to establish their authority. They developed a host of tools—the lie detector, psychotherapy, an array of personality tests, and more—for making deception more transparent in the courts and elsewhere. Pettit’s study illuminates the intimate connections between the scientific discipline and the marketplace during a crucial period in the development of market culture. With its broad research and engaging tales of treachery, The Science of Deception will appeal to scholars and general readers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022692374140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226923758423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226923758/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles